{"title_page": "Zhang Junti", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- see Template:Infobox writer -->\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n| name        = Zhang Junti\n| native_name = \u5f20\u541b\u608c\n| native_name_lang = zh-hans\n| pseudonym   = Jin Ren ({{zh|s=\u91d1\u4eba|labels=no}})<br>Tian Feng ({{zh|s=\u7530\u4e30|labels=no}})\n| birth_name  = Zhang Shaoyan ({{zh|s=\u5f20\u5c11\u5ca9|labels=no}})\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1910|4|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Nangong|Nangong County]], [[Hebei]], [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|China]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1971|8|13|1910|4|25}}\n| death_place = [[Shangluo]], [[Shaanxi]], China\n| resting_place= \n| occupation = Translator\n| nationality= Chinese\n| language   = [[Chinese language|Chinese]], Russian\n| education  = \n| alma_mater = Harbin Special Administrative Law School\n| period     =  \n| genre      = \n| subject    = \n| movement   = \n| notableworks= ''[[And Quiet Flows the Don]]''\n| spouse     = <!-- {{marriage||}} -->\n| children   = \n| relatives  = \n| awards     = <!--  {{Awards|award= |year= |title= }} -->\n| website    = <!--  {{URL|website}} -->\n| partner    =  \n| signature   =  \n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Zhang (surname)|Zhang]]}}\n'''Zhang Junti''' ({{zh|s=\u5f20\u541b\u608c|t=\u5f35\u541b\u608c|p=Zh\u0101ng J\u016bnt\u00ec}}; 25 April 1910 - 13 August 1971), also known by his pen name '''Jin Ren''' and '''Tian Feng''', was a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] translator. Zhang was the first person from China to translate Russian novelist [[Mikhail Alexandrovich Sholokhov]]'s ''[[And Quiet Flows the Don]]'' to Chinese language.\n\n==Biography==\nZhang was born '''Zhang Shaoyan''' ({{zh|s=\u5f20\u5c11\u5ca9|labels=no}}) in [[Nangong|Nangong County]], [[Hebei]], on April 25, 1910.<ref name=\"tiger\">{{cite news|author=Li Jianjun |url=http://culture.china.com.cn/book/2010-03/25/content_19688041.htm |script-title=zh:\u7ffb\u8bd1\u5bb6\u91d1\u4eba\uff1a\u201c\u8fd1\u4ec1\u201d\u8010\u4eba\u5bfb\u5473 |work=jyb.cn |date=2010-03-10 |language=zh}}</ref> He lost his mother when he was young and wandered with his father in [[Jiangsu]], [[Anhui]], [[Henan]] and [[Beijing]]. He primarily studied at the [[Beijing Normal University|Primary School Affiliated to Beijing Normal University]] and secondary studied at the Beijing Anhui High School.\n\nIn 1927 he came to [[Harbin]], capital of [[northeast China]]'s [[Heilongjiang]] province, where he worked as an employee in a law court. In 1930 he enrolled at Harbin Special Administrative Law School, where he majored in law. He started to publish works during that time. In 1933, under the influence of young writers such as Luo Feng ({{zh|s=\u7f57\u70fd|labels=no}}), [[Jin Jianxiao]], [[Jiang Chunfang]], Shu Qun ({{zh|s=\u8212\u7fa4|labels=no}}), [[Xiao Hong]] and [[Xiao Jun]], he began to translate [[Russian literature|Russian classical and modern literature]]. In 1935, due to the translation of progressive books, he was supervised by the Japanese police. In 1937, he left for [[Shanghai]], where he taught at Shanghai Zhonghua Girls' High School and Peicheng Girls' High School. During the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]], he translated [[Mikhail Alexandrovich Sholokhov]]'s ''[[And Quiet Flows the Don]]''. In 1942 he became director of the Department of Justice in Jiangsu. He returned to Shanghai in the following year. After Japan surrendered, he came to the northeast China and served as Secretary of the CPC Shenyang Underground Municipal Committee. When [[Liu Baiyu]] visited him in 1946, they were secretly followed by the [[Kuomintang]]. After Liu Baiyu left, he was arrested by the Kuomintang. In 1947, he was released in exchange for Zhao Junmai ({{zh|s=\u8d75\u541b\u8fc8|labels=no}}), the mayor of Changchun, who was captured by the [[People's Liberation Army]]. Then he served as vice-minister and publishing minister of Research Department of Northeast Cultural Association. In 1948 he became director of the Ministry of Justice of the Northeast Administrative Committee, and held that office until November 1949, when he was appointed deputy director of Compilation Bureau of the [[General Administration of Press and Publication]].\n\nAfter the founding of the Communist State, he successively worked in the Times Publishing House and [[People's Literature Publishing House]]. In 1952 he joined the [[China Writers Association]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Zhang Junti |language=zh|url=http://www.chinawriter.com.cn/n1/2016/0627/c404953-28497113.html |accessdate=10 August 2019|year=2015|work=chinawriter}}</ref> During the [[Cultural Revolution]], he suffered [[political persecution]] and was sent to the [[May Seventh Cadre Schools]] to do farm works in [[Shangluo]], [[Shaanxi]], he died there on August 13, 1971.<ref name=\"tiger\"/>\n\n==Translations==\n* ''[[And Quiet Flows the Don]]'' ({{lang|zh-Hans-CN|\u9759\u9759\u7684\u987f\u6cb3}})<ref>{{cite book |language=zh|author=[[Mikhail Alexandrovich Sholokhov]] |title=And Quiet Flows the Don |year=2015 |publisher=People's Literature Publishing House |location=Beijing |pages= |isbn=9787020104505}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhang, Junti}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Nangong]]\n[[Category:Writers from Hebei]]\n[[Category:Russian\u2013Chinese translators]]\n[[Category:People persecuted to death during the Cultural Revolution]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China translators]]\n[[Category:Republic of China translators]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- see Template:Infobox writer -->\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n| name        = Zhang Junti\n| native_name = \u5f20\u541b\u608c\n| native_name_lang = zh-hans\n| pseudonym   = Jin Ren ({{zh|s=\u91d1\u4eba|labels=no}})<br>Tian Feng ({{zh|s=\u7530\u4e30|labels=no}})\n| birth_name  = Zhang Shaoyan ({{zh|s=\u5f20\u5c11\u5ca9|labels=no}})\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1910|4|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Nangong|Nangong County]], [[Hebei]], [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|China]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1971|8|13|1910|4|25}}\n| death_place = [[Shangluo]], [[Shaanxi]], China\n| resting_place= \n| occupation = Translator\n| nationality= Chinese\n| language   = [[Chinese language|Chinese]], Russian\n| education  = \n| alma_mater = Harbin Special Administrative Law School\n| period     =  \n| genre      = \n| subject    = \n| movement   = \n| notableworks= ''[[And Quiet Flows the Don]]''\n| spouse     = <!-- {{marriage||}} -->\n| children   = \n| relatives  = \n| awards     = <!--  {{Awards|award= |year= |title= }} -->\n| website    = <!--  {{URL|website}} -->\n| partner    =  \n| signature   =  \n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Zhang (surname)|Zhang]]}}\n'''Zhang Junti''' ({{zh|s=\u5f20\u541b\u608c|t=\u5f35\u541b\u608c|p=Zh\u0101ng J\u016bnt\u00ec}}; 25 April 1910 - 13 August 1971), also known by his pen name '''Jin Ren''' and '''Tian Feng''', was a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] translator. Zhang was the first person from China to translate Russian novelist [[Mikhail Alexandrovich Sholokhov]]'s ''[[And Quiet Flows the Don]]'' to Chinese language.\n\n==Biography==\nZhang was born '''Zhang Shaoyan''' ({{zh|s=\u5f20\u5c11\u5ca9|labels=no}}) in [[Nangong|Nangong County]], [[Hebei]], on April 25, 1910.<ref name=\"tiger\">{{cite news|author=Li Jianjun |url=http://culture.china.com.cn/book/2010-03/25/content_19688041.htm |script-title=zh:\u7ffb\u8bd1\u5bb6\u91d1\u4eba\uff1a\u201c\u8fd1\u4ec1\u201d\u8010\u4eba\u5bfb\u5473 |work=jyb.cn |date=2010-03-10 |language=zh}}</ref> He lost his mother when he was young and wandered with his father in [[Jiangsu]], [[Anhui]], [[Henan]] and [[Beijing]]. He primarily studied at the [[Beijing Normal University|Primary School Affiliated to Beijing Normal University]] and secondary studied at the Beijing Anhui High School.\n\nIn 1927 he came to [[Harbin]], capital of [[northeast China]]'s [[Heilongjiang]] province, where he worked as an employee in a law court. In 1930 he enrolled at Harbin Special Administrative Law School, where he majored in law. He started to publish works during that time. In 1933, under the influence of young writers such as Luo Feng ({{zh|s=\u7f57\u70fd|labels=no}}), [[Jin Jianxiao]], [[Jiang Chunfang]], Shu Qun ({{zh|s=\u8212\u7fa4|labels=no}}), [[Xiao Hong]] and [[Xiao Jun]], he began to translate [[Russian literature|Russian classical and modern literature]]. In 1935, due to the translation of progressive books, he was supervised by the Japanese police. In 1937, he left for [[Shanghai]], where he taught at Shanghai Zhonghua Girls' High School and Peicheng Girls' High School. During the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]], he translated [[Mikhail Alexandrovich Sholokhov]]'s ''[[And Quiet Flows the Don]]''. In 1942 he became director of the Department of Justice in Jiangsu. He returned to Shanghai in the following year. After Japan surrendered, he came to the northeast China and served as Secretary of the CPC Shenyang Underground Municipal Committee. When [[Liu Baiyu]] visited him in 1946, they were secretly followed by the [[Kuomintang]]. After Liu Baiyu left, he was arrested by the Kuomintang. In 1947, he was released in exchange for Zhao Junmai ({{zh|s=\u8d75\u541b\u8fc8|labels=no}}), the mayor of Changchun, who was captured by the [[People's Liberation Army]]. Then he served as vice-minister and publishing minister of Research Department of Northeast Cultural Association. In 1948 he became director of the Ministry of Justice of the Northeast Administrative Committee, and held that office until November 1949, when he was appointed deputy director of Compilation Bureau of the [[General Administration of Press and Publication]].\n\nAfter the founding of the Communist State, he successively worked in the Times Publishing House and [[People's Literature Publishing House]]. In 1952 he joined the [[China Writers Association]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Zhang Junti |language=zh|url=http://www.chinawriter.com.cn/n1/2016/0627/c404953-28497113.html |accessdate=10 August 2019|year=2015|work=chinawriter}}</ref> During the [[Cultural Revolution]], he suffered [[political persecution]] and was sent to the [[May Seventh Cadre Schools]] to do farm works in [[Shangluo]], [[Shaanxi]], he died there on August 13, 1971.<ref name=\"tiger\"/>\n\n==Translations==\n* ''[[And Quiet Flows the Don]]'' ({{lang|zh-Hans-CN|\u9759\u9759\u7684\u987f\u6cb3}})<ref>{{cite book |language=zh|author=[[Mikhail Alexandrovich Sholokhov]] |title=And Quiet Flows the Don |year=2015 |publisher=People's Literature Publishing House |location=Beijing |pages= |isbn=9787020104505}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhang, Junti}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Nangong]]\n[[Category:Writers from Hebei]]\n[[Category:Russian\u2013Chinese translators]]\n[[Category:People persecuted to death during the Cultural Revolution]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China translators]]\n[[Category:Republic of China translators]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhang_Junti"}
{"title_page": "Cataratas del Iguaz\u00fa International Airport", "text_new": "{{for|the airport serving [[Foz do Igua\u00e7u]], [[Brazil]]|Foz do Igua\u00e7u International Airport}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name          = Cataratas del Iguaz\u00fa International Airport\n| nativename    = {{lang|es|Aeropuerto Internacional Cataratas del Iguaz\u00fa}}\n| image         = File:Aeropuerto Puerto Iguazu.JPG\n| IATA          = IGR\n| ICAO          = SARI\n|pushpin_map    = Argentina\n|pushpin_label  = '''IGR'''\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in Argentina\n|coordinates    = {{coord|25|44|10|S|54|28|25|W|display=inline,title}}\n| type          = Public\n| owner         = \n| operator      = [[Aeropuertos Argentina 2000]]\n| city-served   = [[Puerto Iguaz\u00fa]], [[Argentina]]\n| location      = \n| elevation-f   = 916\n| elevation-m   = \n| website       = \n| metric-rwy    = y\n| r1-number     = 13/31\n| r1-length-m   = 3300\n| r1-length-f   = \n| r1-surface    = Asphalt\n| stat-year     = {{small|2016}}\n| stat1-header  = Passengers\n| stat1-data    = 893,945<ref>http://www.aeropuertosarg.com.ar/2014/04/24-millones-de-inversion-para-nueva-torre-de-control-en-puerto-iguazu/</ref>\n| stat2-header  = Passenger change 15\u201316\n| stat2-data    = {{increase}}3.6%\n| stat3-header  = Aircraft movements\n| stat3-data    = 8,721\n| stat4-header  = Movements change 15\u201316\n| stat4-data    = {{increase}}4%\n| footnotes     = Sources: AIP<ref name=AIP>{{cite web |url= http://www.cra.gov.ar/dta/ais/aip/docs/172.pdf |title= SARI \u2013 CATARATAS DEL IGUAZ\u00da / Mayor D. Carlos Eduardo Krause |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110531174911/http://www.cra.gov.ar/dta/ais/aip/docs/172.pdf |archivedate= 31 May 2011 |df= dmy-all }} at [[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] Argentina {{in lang|es}}</ref> ORSNA<ref name=ORSNA>''[http://www.orsna.gov.ar/aeropuertos/infoaeropuertos.aspx?cod_aero=16 Aeropuerto de Misiones \"Cataratas del Iguazu\"] {{webarchive |url=https://archive.is/20121127132213/http://www.orsna.gov.ar/aeropuertos/infoaeropuertos.aspx?cod_aero=16 |date=27 November 2012 }}'' at ''Organismo Regulador del Sistema Nacional de Aeropuertos (ORSNA)'' {{in lang|es}}</ref> WAD<ref name=WAD>{{WAD|SARI|source=[[DAFIF]]}}</ref> GCM<ref name=GCM>{{GCM|IGR|Cataratas del Iguaz\u00fa International Airport}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Cataratas del Iguaz\u00fa International Airport''' ({{lang-es|link=no|Aeropuerto Internacional Cataratas del Iguaz\u00fa}}) {{airport codes|IGR|SARI}}, also known as '''Mayor Carlos Eduardo Krause Airport''',<ref name=AIP /><ref name=WAD /> is an airport in [[Misiones Province]], [[Argentina]] serving the city of [[Puerto Iguaz\u00fa]] and providing access to the nearby [[Iguaz\u00fa Falls]] ({{lang-es|link=no|Cataratas del Iguaz\u00fa}}). It is the easternmost Argentine airport served by scheduled flights.\nThe airport covers an area of {{convert|1804|ha|acre|abbr=on}} and is operated by [[Aeropuertos Argentina 2000]]<ref name=AIP /><ref name=ORSNA />\n\nThe airport is in forested countryside {{convert|16|km|0}} southeast of Puerto Iguaz\u00fa, and {{convert|6|km|0}} south of the falls. The Cataratas Del Iguazu [[VOR-DME]] (Ident: '''IGU''') is located on the field.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cataratas Del Iguazu VOR |url=http://ourairports.com/navaids/IGU/Cataratas_Del_Iguazu_VOR-DME_AR/ |website=Our Airports |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n[[File:Aeropuerto Iguaz\u00fa - panoramio.jpg|thumb|alt=View of the terminal ramp and jetways from an aircraft taxiing in to park|Airport terminal, airside]]\n{{Airport-dest-list\n<!-- -->\n|[[Aerol\u00edneas Argentinas]] | [[Aeroparque Jorge Newbery|Buenos Aires\u2013Aeroparque]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Europa]] | [[Silvio Pettirossi International Airport|Asunci\u00f3n]], [[Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport|Madrid]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Andes L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas]] | [[Aeroparque Jorge Newbery|