ms|publisher=Da Capo|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-306-81096-1|url=https://archive.org/details/alistnationalsoc00jayc}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Prideaux|first=James|year=1996|title=Knowing Hepburn and Other Curious Experiences|publisher=Faber and Faber|location=Boston, MA|isbn=978-0-571-19892-4|authorlink=James Prideaux|url=https://archive.org/details/knowinghepburnot00prid}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Verlhac| first=Pierre-Henri| title=Katharine Hepburn: A Life in Pictures| publisher=Chronicle Books|location=San Francisco, CA|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8118-6947-8}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q56016|b=no|wikt=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|n=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|31}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Guardian topic}}\n* {{worldcat|id=lccn-n50-38123}}\n* {{MHL catalog|67192}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111015220356/http://www.npg.si.edu/exhibit/hepburn/ \"One Life: Kate, A Centennial Celebration\"]. Online exhibition from the National Portrait Gallery, Smithsonian Institution\n* [http://archives.nypl.org/the/21820 Katharine Hepburn papers, circa 1854\u20131997 and undated], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n* {{books-inline|Katharine Hepburn|Katharine Hepburn}}\n\n{{Katharine Hepburn}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Katharine Hepburn|Awards for Katharine Hepburn]]\n| list =\n{{Academy Award Best Actress}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Actress 1960\u20131979}}\n{{Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation f\u00e9minine 1960\u20131979}}\n{{Connecticut Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{David di Donatello for Best Foreign Actress}}\n{{EmmyAward MiniseriesLeadActress 1950\u20131975}}\n{{Hasty Pudding Woman of the Year}}\n{{Kennedy Center Honorees 1990s}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actress}}\n{{People's Choice Award for Favorite Movie Actress}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward LifeAchievement 1960\u20131979}}\n{{Volpi Cup for Best Actress}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hepburn, Katharine}}\n[[Category:Katharine Hepburn| ]]\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American radio actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American Shakespearean actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Actress BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Bryn Mawr College alumni]]\n[[Category:Burials at Cedar Hill Cemetery (Hartford, Connecticut)]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Connecticut Democrats]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello winners]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Deaths from esophageal cancer]]\n[[Category:Kennedy Center honorees]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actress in a Miniseries or Movie Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Old Saybrook, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:RKO Pictures contract players]]\n[[Category:Screen Actors Guild Life Achievement Award]]\n[[Category:Volpi Cup for Best Actress winners]]\n[[Category:Volpi Cup winners]]\n", "name_user": "Textorus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBreaking into theatre (1928\u20131932):diction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katharine_Hepburn"}
{"title_page": "Amparo, S\u00e3o Paulo", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name            = Amparo\n| native_name             = \n| settlement_type         = [[Municipalities of Brazil|Municipality]]\n| image_shield            = AmparoBrasao.png\n| image_flag               = AmparoBand.jpg\n| image_skyline           = Vista_amparo.JPG\n| image_caption           = View of Amparo, S\u00e3o Paulo\n| image_map               = SaoPaulo Municip Amparo.svg\n| map_caption             = Location in S\u00e3o Paulo  state\n| pushpin_map             = Brazil\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Brazil\n| coordinates             = {{coord|22|42|11|S|46|45|54|W|region:BR|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = Brazil\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Regions of Brazil|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Southeast Region, Brazil|Southeast]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[States of Brazil|State]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Mesoregions of Brazil|Mesoregion]]\n| subdivision_name3       = \n| subdivision_type4       = [[Microregion (Brazil)|Microregion]]\n| subdivision_name4       = \n| subdivision_type5       = [[Metropolitan area#Brazil|Metrop. region]]\n| subdivision_name5       = \n| established_title       = Founded\n| established_date        = April 8, 1829\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name             = \n| elevation_m             = \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 445\n| area_metro_km2          = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 70280\n| population_as_of        = 2015\n| population_metro        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| blank_name_sec1         = [[Human Development Index|HDI]] \n| blank_info_sec1         = \n| timezone1               = [[Time in Brazil|BRT]]\n| utc_offset1             = -03:00\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Daylight saving time in Brazil|BRST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = -02:00\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in Brazil|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = [[List of dialling codes in Brazil|Area code]]\n| area_code               = \n| website                 = \n}}\n'''Amparo''' is a [[Brazil]]ian [[Municipalities of Brazil|municipality]] in the state of [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]]. The population is of 70,280 (2015 est.) in an area of 445 km\u00b2.<ref>[http://cod.ibge.gov.br/234XN Instituto Brasileiro de Geografia e Estat\u00edstica]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The city is the seat of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Amparo]].\n\nThe city is part of the \"Water-Circuit\", a cluster of towns in S\u00e3o Paulo state which are famous for natural fountains and water wells. One of the main events in the city is the Winter Festival, when some stages are set over the main plaza and presentations are scheduled for the whole month of July. All kinds of music bands and artists are invited to the city, from [[M\u00fasica sertaneja|sertanejo]] (a Brazilian form of country music) and [[heavy metal (music)|heavy metal]] to [[Ballet]]. Although the event is more dedicated to the city local residents, it attracts tourists from other regions.\n\nAmparo is located about 50 kilometers from [[Campinas]] and 120 kilometers from [[S\u00e3o Paulo]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|Amparo (S\u00e3o Paulo)}}\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Amparo}}\n\n{{S\u00e3o Paulo state|Campinas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amparo, Sao Paulo}}\n[[Category:Municipalities in S\u00e3o Paulo (state)]]\n\n{{SaoPauloState-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name            = Amparo\n| native_name             = \n| settlement_type         = [[Municipalities of Brazil|Municipality]]\n| image_shield            = AmparoBrasao.png\n| image_flag               = AmparoBand.jpg\n| image_skyline           = Vista_amparo.JPG\n| image_caption           = View of Amparo, S\u00e3o Paulo\n| image_map               = SaoPaulo Municip Amparo.svg\n| map_caption             = Location in S\u00e3o Paulo  state\n| pushpin_map             = Brazil\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Brazil\n| coordinates             = {{coord|22|42|11|S|46|45|54|W|region:BR|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = Brazil\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Regions of Brazil|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Southeast Region, Brazil|Southeast]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[States of Brazil|State]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Mesoregions of Brazil|Mesoregion]]\n| subdivision_name3       = \n| subdivision_type4       = [[Microregion (Brazil)|Microregion]]\n| subdivision_name4       = \n| subdivision_type5       = [[Metropolitan area#Brazil|Metrop. region]]\n| subdivision_name5       = \n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name             = \n| elevation_m             = \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 445\n| area_metro_km2          = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 70280\n| population_as_of        = 2015\n| population_metro        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| blank_name_sec1         = [[Human Development Index|HDI]] \n| blank_info_sec1         = \n| timezone1               = [[Time in Brazil|BRT]]\n| utc_offset1             = -03:00\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Daylight saving time in Brazil|BRST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = -02:00\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in Brazil|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = [[List of dialling codes in Brazil|Area code]]\n| area_code               = \n| website                 = \n}}\n'''Amparo''' is a [[Brazil]]ian [[Municipalities of Brazil|municipality]] in the state of [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]]. The population is of 70,280 (2015 est.) in an area of 445 km\u00b2.<ref>[http://cod.ibge.gov.br/234XN Instituto Brasileiro de Geografia e Estat\u00edstica]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The city is the seat of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Amparo]].\n\nThe city is part of the \"Water-Circuit\", a cluster of towns in S\u00e3o Paulo state which are famous for natural fountains and water wells. One of the main events in the city is the Winter Festival, when some stages are set over the main plaza and presentations are scheduled for the whole month of July. All kinds of music bands and artists are invited to the city, from [[M\u00fasica sertaneja|sertanejo]] (a Brazilian form of country music) and [[heavy metal (music)|heavy metal]] to [[Ballet]]. Although the event is more dedicated to the city local residents, it attracts tourists from other regions.\n\nAmparo is located about 50 kilometers from [[Campinas]] and 120 kilometers from [[S\u00e3o Paulo]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|Amparo (S\u00e3o Paulo)}}\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Amparo}}\n\n{{S\u00e3o Paulo state|Campinas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amparo, Sao Paulo}}\n[[Category:Municipalities in S\u00e3o Paulo (state)]]\n\n{{SaoPauloState-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Evanjlima", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amparo,_S%C3%A3o_Paulo"}
{"title_page": "Sagon Penn", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=April 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n'''Sagon Penn''' (1962 - July 4 2002) was a martial arts expert<ref name=\"https://www.workers.org/2018/0...\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.workers.org/2018/08/38844/ |title=San Diego remembers Sagon Penn |last=Odom |first=M. Matsemela-Ali |last2=Muhammad |first2=Carl |date=2018-08-30 |website=Workers World |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and community leader from [[Southeast San Diego]] who worked as a karate teacher for children in the early 80's.<ref name=\"2002jul06\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-sagon-penn-couldnt-have-life-2002jul06-story.html|title=Sagon Penn 'couldn't have a life'|date=2002-07-06|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Penn was subsequently acquitted for the 1985 shooting death of a San Diego Police officer, the attempted murder of another officer and the attempted murder of a civilian ride along.<ref name=\"apnews\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/9038a9cef3aeee85a80597839e960620|title=Acquittal in Second Trial for Officer's Slaying|work=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/07/17/Man-acquitted-in-racially-charged-cop-killing/7770553492800/|title=Man acquitted in racially charged cop killing|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\"ODMP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/11276-agent-thomas-edward-riggs|title=Agent Thomas Edward Riggs|website=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>   \n\n== Multiple altercations and death of officer ==\nIn 1985 Penn's vehicle was pulled over in the [[Encanto, San Diego|Encanto area]] during a traffic stop by San Diego Police officer's Thomas Riggs and Donovan Jacobs. Civilian police ride along Sara Pina-Ruiz was in the squad car when a physical altercation ensued resulting in Penn shooting and killing officer Thomas Riggs with his own service revolver, shooting and injuring civilian ride along Sara Pina-Ruiz and running over and injuring officer Donovan Jacobs with the police car as Penn, who was behind the wheel fled the scene.<ref name=\"apnews\" /><ref name=\"ODMP\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/07/17/Man-acquitted-in-racially-charged-cop-killing/7770553492800/|title=Man acquitted in racially charged cop killing|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Later that day Penn voluntarily surrendered himself to Police.\n\n== Trials ==\nRepresented by defense attorney Milton Silverman<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-03-02-me-1447-story.html|title=Penn Defense Could Rank With County's Most Costly|date=1986-03-02|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Penn was acquitted in 1986 on the more serious murder charge for killing officer Riggs and in a second trial in 1987 acquitted of all lesser charges. <ref name=\"apnews\" />\n\n== Community review board on police practices ==\nAfter the final verdicts, Superior Court Judge J. Morgan Lester gave unflinching criticism of the San Diego Police Department conduct in the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-07-21-me-5199-story.html|title=Penn Trial Judge Assails Conduct of Police|date=1987-07-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> As a direct result of such criticism the Mayor and City Council at the time appointed citizens to a Citizens Advisory Board which ultimately led to the formation of the [https://www.sandiego.gov/communityreviewboard/about Community Review Board on Police Practices]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/communityreviewboard/about|title=About the Board {{!}} Community Review Board on Police Practices {{!}} City of San Diego Official Website|website=www.sandiego.gov|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=April 2020}}   Officer Riggs was the only officer killed in the line of duty from the [[San Diego Police Department]] in 1985<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/11276-agent-thomas-edward-riggs|title=Agent Thomas Edward Riggs|website=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and there was no other reported officer involved shooting in the city that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/11276-agent-thomas-edward-riggs|title=Agent Thomas Edward Riggs|website=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn  July 4 2002,<ref name=\"https://www.workers.org/2018/0...\" /> Sagon Penn reportedly took his own life in what authorities determined was a suicide overdose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-sagon-penn-found-dead-apparent-suicide-2002jul05-story.html|title=Sagon Penn found dead in apparent suicide|date=2002-07-05|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=April 2020}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n'''Sagon Penn''' (1962 - July 4 2002) was a martial arts expert<ref name=\"https://www.workers.org/2018/0...\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.workers.org/2018/08/38844/ |title=San Diego remembers Sagon Penn |last=Odom |first=M. Matsemela-Ali |last2=Muhammad |first2=Carl |date=2018-08-30 |website=Workers World |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and community leader from [[Southeast San Diego]] who worked as a karate teacher for children in the early 80's.<ref name=\"2002jul06\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-sagon-penn-couldnt-have-life-2002jul06-story.html|title=Sagon Penn 'couldn't have a life'|date=2002-07-06|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Penn was subsequently acquitted for the 1985 shooting death of a San Diego Police officer, the attempted murder of another officer and the attempted murder of a civilian ride along.<ref name=\"apnews\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/9038a9cef3aeee85a80597839e960620|title=Acquittal in Second Trial for Officer's Slaying|work=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/07/17/Man-acquitted-in-racially-charged-cop-killing/7770553492800/|title=Man acquitted in racially charged cop killing|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\"ODMP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/11276-agent-thomas-edward-riggs|title=Agent Thomas Edward Riggs|website=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>   \n\n== Multiple altercations and death of officer ==\nIn 1985 Penn's vehicle was pulled over in the [[Encanto, San Diego|Encanto area]] during a traffic stop by San Diego Police officer's Thomas Riggs and Donovan Jacobs. Civilian police ride along Sara Pina-Ruiz was in the squad car when a physical altercation ensued resulting in Penn shooting and killing officer Thomas Riggs with his own service revolver, shooting and injuring civilian ride along Sara Pina-Ruiz and running over and injuring officer Donovan Jacobs with the police car as Penn, who was behind the wheel fled the scene.<ref name=\"apnews\" /><ref name=\"ODMP\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/07/17/Man-acquitted-in-racially-charged-cop-killing/7770553492800/|title=Man acquitted in racially charged cop killing|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Later that day Penn voluntarily surrendered himself to Police.\n\n== Trials ==\nRepresented by defense attorney Milton Silverman<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-03-02-me-1447-story.html|title=Penn Defense Could Rank With County's Most Costly|date=1986-03-02|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Penn was acquitted in 1986 on the more serious murder charge for killing officer Riggs and in a second trial in 1987 acquitted of all lesser charges. <ref name=\"apnews\" />\n\n== Community review board on police practices ==\nAfter the final verdicts, Superior Court Judge J. Morgan Lester gave unflinching criticism of the San Diego Police Department conduct in the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-07-21-me-5199-story.html|title=Penn Trial Judge Assails Conduct of Police|date=1987-07-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> As a direct result of such criticism the Mayor and City Council at the time appointed citizens to a Citizens Advisory Board which ultimately led to the formation of the Community Review Board on Police Practices<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiego.gov/communityreviewboard/about|title=About the Board {{!}} Community Review Board on Police Practices {{!}} City of San Diego Official Website|website=www.sandiego.gov|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=April 2020}}   Officer Riggs was the only officer killed in the line of duty from the [[San Diego Police Department]] in 1985<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/11276-agent-thomas-edward-riggs|title=Agent Thomas Edward Riggs|website=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and there was no other reported officer involved shooting in the city that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/11276-agent-thomas-edward-riggs|title=Agent Thomas Edward Riggs|website=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nOn  July 4 2002,<ref name=\"https://www.workers.org/2018/0...\" /> Sagon Penn reportedly took his own life in what authorities determined was a suicide overdose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-sagon-penn-found-dead-apparent-suicide-2002jul05-story.html|title=Sagon Penn found dead in apparent suicide|date=2002-07-05|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Spiritletters", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sagon_Penn"}
{"title_page": "William Savage", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n\n'''William Savage''' (1720 \u2013 27 July 1789) was an [[English people|English]] composer, organist, and singer of the [[18th century]]. He sang as a boy [[boy soprano|treble]] and [[alto]], a [[countertenor]], and as a [[bass (voice)|bass]]. He is best remembered for his association with the composer [[George Frideric Handel]], in whose [[oratorio]]s Savage sang.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Singer===\n[[Image:Haendel.jpg|thumb|210px|The composer [[George Frideric Handel]], who composed many different roles in his [[operas]] and [[oratorios]] for Savage (1733)]]\nSavage first came to prominence as a boy treble in 1735, singing in a revival of Handel's ''[[Athalia]]'' and in ''[[Alcina]]'' during the composer's Covent Garden season. The role of Oberto in ''Alcina'' was composed with his voice particularly in mind. After his voice had broken, he initially continued his career singing as an alto ([[countertenor]]), and later turned into a bass. As a countertenor he performed possibly the small roles of La Fortuna and Childerico in Handel's operas, ''[[Giustino (Handel)|Giustino]]'' (1737) and ''[[Faramondo]]'' (1738),<ref>Grove. Savage's countertenor performing the role of Childerico is also stated by Hogwood (p. 146). According to the English conductor, \"the countertenor voice was not typical of ''opera seria'' and Savage perhaps took the small [[soprano]] part of Childerico because of the problems <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[impresario]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> [[John James Heidegger|Heidegger]] encountered in casting it. It is certainly no historical precedent; in a similar dilemma Handel would normally have transposed or transferred a castrato part to a female singer\". According to [[Anthony Hicks]], however, the role of the goddess Fortuna was instead his last appearance as a treble, while the minor soprano part of Childerico, which has no arias, was probably sung an octave lower than written, having Savage's voice just broken (articles: ''Giustino'' (ii) and ''Faramondo'', in [[Stanley Sadie]] (ed), ''[[The New Grove Dictionary of Opera]]'', New York, Oxford University Press, 1997, II, pp. 121 e 440\u2013441).</ref> and also appeared in the first performance of  ''[[Israel in Egypt]]'' (1739), as well as in revivals of other Handel oratorios.<ref name=\"countertenor\">The information for these performances and their dates comes from http://gfhandel.org/.</ref> As a bass, he created the title role in ''[[Imeneo]]'' (1740), the role of Fenice in ''[[Deidamia (opera)|Deidamia]]'' (1741)<ref name=\"Grove\">Burrows.</ref> and that of Manoa at the premiere of the oratorio ''[[Samson (oratorio)|Samson]]'' (1743).<ref name=\"countertenor\"/> The 18th-century musicologist [[Charles Burney]] described Savage's voice as a \"powerful and not unpleasant bass\".<ref name=\"Grove\"/> The description of his pupil R. J. S. Stevens is more complimentary: he describes Savage as possessing \"a pleasant voice of two octaves\", and details that Savage sang with \"clear articulation, perfect intonation, great volubility of voice, and chaste and good expression\".<ref name=\"Grove\"/>\n\nIn 1740 Savage was elected organist of [[St Mary-at-Finchley Church|Finchley Church]]; in 1744 he became a bass (gentleman-in-ordinary) in the [[Chapel Royal]]'s choir and in 1748 he was appointed Vicar Choral, Almoner and Master of the Choristers at [[St Paul's Cathedral]],<ref>Argent, Mark (ed), ''Recollections of R. J. S. Stevens: An Organist in Georgian London'', Carbondale, Southern Illinois University Press, 1992, p. 300.</ref> where he influenced many of the following generation of high-class musicians. In 1777 he retired to [[Kent]]. He returned to London in 1780 to teach music but was not as successful as in previous years.<ref name=\"Grove\"/> He remained in London until his death there.\n\nSome music in Savage's collection was given to the [[Royal Academy of Music]] upon the death of his student, [[R. J. S. Stevens]], in 1837. The collection included ''[[Gloria (Handel)|Gloria]]'', a composition identified as Handel's work only in 2001.<ref>[http://gfhandel.org/gloria.htm ''Gloria in excelsis Deo'', \"The Newly Discovered Musical Composition by Handel.\"] See also [http://www.kwella.co.uk/gloria.htm this 2001 preface by Clifford Bartlett.]</ref>\n\n===Composer===\nSavage was also a moderately prolific composer. He composed many [[anthems]] and other church music. His anthem \"O Lord my God\" is his most ambitious work and is written for accompaniment by [[string orchestra]]. He also composed music for solo violin and various [[Canon (music)|canons]], [[Catch (music)|catches]] and rounds, composed for the [[Noblemen and Gentlemen's Catch Club]], of which Savage was a member. A more idiosyncratic piece was his \"On the very first of May\", set to nonsense poetry written by his wife.<ref name=\"Grove\"/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles King (composer)|Charles King]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[St Paul's Cathedral#Almoners and masters of the choristers|Almoner and Master of the Choristers]] of [[St Paul's Cathedral]]\n|years=1748\u20131773}}\n{{s-aft|after=Robert Hudson}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Donald Burrows: \"Savage, William\", in ''Grove Music Online'' ed L. Macy (accessed 5 January 2007) grovemusic.com, subscription access.\n*Hogwood, Christopher (2007). ''Handel'' (Revised edition), Thames and Hudson, {{ISBN|978-0-500-28681-4}}.\n*Stevens, R.J.S. and Henry George Farmer: \"A Forgotten Composer of Anthems: William Savage (1720\u201389)\" in ''Music & Letters'', Vol. 17, No. 3 (Jul. 1936), pp.&nbsp;188\u201399 (available via [[JSTOR]])\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Savage, William}}\n[[Category:1720 births]]\n[[Category:1789 deaths]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:English classical organists]]\n[[Category:Male organists]]\n[[Category:English Baroque composers]]\n[[Category:English opera singers]]\n[[Category:Operatic countertenors]]\n[[Category:Operatic basses]]\n[[Category:Gentlemen of the Chapel Royal]]\n[[Category:18th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:18th-century keyboardists]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n\n'''William Savage''' (1720 \u2013 27 July 1789) was an [[English people|English]] composer, organist, and singer of the 18th century. He sang as a boy [[boy soprano|treble]] and [[alto]], a [[countertenor]], and as a [[bass (voice)|bass]]. He is best remembered for his association with the composer [[George Frideric Handel]], in whose [[oratorio]]s Savage sang.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Singer===\n[[Image:Haendel.jpg|thumb|210px|The composer [[George Frideric Handel]], who composed many different roles in his [[operas]] and [[oratorios]] for Savage (1733)]]\nSavage first came to prominence as a boy treble in 1735, singing in a revival of Handel's ''[[Athalia]]'' and in ''[[Alcina]]'' during the composer's Covent Garden season. The role of Oberto in ''Alcina'' was composed with his voice particularly in mind. After his voice had broken, he initially continued his career singing as an alto ([[countertenor]]), and later turned into a bass. As a countertenor he performed possibly the small roles of La Fortuna and Childerico in Handel's operas, ''[[Giustino (Handel)|Giustino]]'' (1737) and ''[[Faramondo]]'' (1738),<ref>Grove. Savage's countertenor performing the role of Childerico is also stated by Hogwood (p. 146). According to the English conductor, \"the countertenor voice was not typical of ''opera seria'' and Savage perhaps took the small [[soprano]] part of Childerico because of the problems <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[impresario]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> [[John James Heidegger|Heidegger]] encountered in casting it. It is certainly no historical precedent; in a similar dilemma Handel would normally have transposed or transferred a castrato part to a female singer\". According to [[Anthony Hicks]], however, the role of the goddess Fortuna was instead his last appearance as a treble, while the minor soprano part of Childerico, which has no arias, was probably sung an octave lower than written, having Savage's voice just broken (articles: ''Giustino'' (ii) and ''Faramondo'', in [[Stanley Sadie]] (ed), ''[[The New Grove Dictionary of Opera]]'', New York, Oxford University Press, 1997, II, pp. 121 e 440\u2013441).</ref> and also appeared in the first performance of  ''[[Israel in Egypt]]'' (1739), as well as in revivals of other Handel oratorios.<ref name=\"countertenor\">The information for these performances and their dates comes from http://gfhandel.org/.</ref> As a bass, he created the title role in ''[[Imeneo]]'' (1740), the role of Fenice in ''[[Deidamia (opera)|Deidamia]]'' (1741)<ref name=\"Grove\">Burrows.</ref> and that of Manoa at the premiere of the oratorio ''[[Samson (oratorio)|Samson]]'' (1743).<ref name=\"countertenor\"/> The 18th-century musicologist [[Charles Burney]] described Savage's voice as a \"powerful and not unpleasant bass\".<ref name=\"Grove\"/> The description of his pupil R. J. S. Stevens is more complimentary: he describes Savage as possessing \"a pleasant voice of two octaves\", and details that Savage sang with \"clear articulation, perfect intonation, great volubility of voice, and chaste and good expression\".<ref name=\"Grove\"/>\n\nIn 1740 Savage was elected organist of [[St Mary-at-Finchley Church|Finchley Church]]; in 1744 he became a bass (gentleman-in-ordinary) in the [[Chapel Royal]]'s choir and in 1748 he was appointed Vicar Choral, Almoner and Master of the Choristers at [[St Paul's Cathedral]],<ref>Argent, Mark (ed), ''Recollections of R. J. S. Stevens: An Organist in Georgian London'', Carbondale, Southern Illinois University Press, 1992, p. 300.</ref> where he influenced many of the following generation of high-class musicians. In 1777 he retired to [[Kent]]. He returned to London in 1780 to teach music but was not as successful as in previous years.<ref name=\"Grove\"/> He remained in London until his death there.\n\nSome music in Savage's collection was given to the [[Royal Academy of Music]] upon the death of his student, [[R. J. S. Stevens]], in 1837. The collection included ''[[Gloria (Handel)|Gloria]]'', a composition identified as Handel's work only in 2001.<ref>[http://gfhandel.org/gloria.htm ''Gloria in excelsis Deo'', \"The Newly Discovered Musical Composition by Handel.\"] See also [http://www.kwella.co.uk/gloria.htm this 2001 preface by Clifford Bartlett.]</ref>\n\n===Composer===\nSavage was also a moderately prolific composer. He composed many [[anthems]] and other church music. His anthem \"O Lord my God\" is his most ambitious work and is written for accompaniment by [[string orchestra]]. He also composed music for solo violin and various [[Canon (music)|canons]], [[Catch (music)|catches]] and rounds, composed for the [[Noblemen and Gentlemen's Catch Club]], of which Savage was a member. A more idiosyncratic piece was his \"On the very first of May\", set to nonsense poetry written by his wife.<ref name=\"Grove\"/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles King (composer)|Charles King]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[St Paul's Cathedral#Almoners and masters of the choristers|Almoner and Master of the Choristers]] of [[St Paul's Cathedral]]\n|years=1748\u20131773}}\n{{s-aft|after=Robert Hudson}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Donald Burrows: \"Savage, William\", in ''Grove Music Online'' ed L. Macy (accessed 5 January 2007) grovemusic.com, subscription access.\n*Hogwood, Christopher (2007). ''Handel'' (Revised edition), Thames and Hudson, {{ISBN|978-0-500-28681-4}}.\n*Stevens, R.J.S. and Henry George Farmer: \"A Forgotten Composer of Anthems: William Savage (1720\u201389)\" in ''Music & Letters'', Vol. 17, No. 3 (Jul. 1936), pp.&nbsp;188\u201399 (available via [[JSTOR]])\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Savage, William}}\n[[Category:1720 births]]\n[[Category:1789 deaths]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:English classical organists]]\n[[Category:Male organists]]\n[[Category:English Baroque composers]]\n[[Category:English opera singers]]\n[[Category:Operatic countertenors]]\n[[Category:Operatic basses]]\n[[Category:Gentlemen of the Chapel Royal]]\n[[Category:18th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:18th-century keyboardists]]\n", "name_user": "Katieb1999", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Savage"}
